OBJECT (JavaScript)

  • Definition
    • An object is a non-primitive value
    • It is a collection of key → value pairs
    • Used to store structured data and optionally behavior (functions)

  • Structure
    • key (property name)
    • value (data or function)

  • Example (plain object)
    • { name: "Alice", age: 20 }

Core Characteristics

  • Stored by reference (not copied directly)
  • Mutable (can be changed after creation)
  • Can contain:
    • primitives
    • other objects
    • arrays
    • functions (methods)

Types of Objects in JavaScript

  • Plain Object (Object Literal)
    • { name: "Alice" }

  • Array (ordered object)
    • [1, 2, 3]

  • Function (callable object)
    • function () {}

  • Class Instance (custom object)
    • new User("Alice")

  • Built-in Objects
    • new Date()
    • new Map()
    • new Set()
    • /abc/ (RegExp)

Not Objects (Primitives)

  • string → "hello"
  • number → 42
  • boolean → true
  • null
  • undefined
  • bigint
  • symbol

Final Mental Model

  • Object = structured container of key-value pairs
  • Can hold both data and behavior
  • Everything that is NOT a primitive is considered an object in JavaScript
